    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Location pages</strong> are individual web pages created for each physical branch or office of a multi-location business. Each page contains that branch's unique address, phone number, hours, staff information, and customer reviews — plus LocalBusiness JSON-LD schema and a link to the corresponding Google Business Profile listing. According to BrightLocal research, businesses with individually optimised location pages generate 20-30% more organic traffic per location than those relying on a single consolidated page.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Traffic lift</div>
            <div class="tms-value">20-30% per location</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Time to rank</div>
            <div class="tms-value">3-6 months</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">A single "Locations" directory page with a list of addresses is not a location page strategy. Each branch needs its own indexable URL, its own content, and its own schema block — otherwise Google has no surface to attach local ranking signals to.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are location pages?</h2>
        <p>Location pages are the website-side counterpart to Google Business Profile listings. Where a GBP listing exists in Google's map index, a location page exists on your domain — and the two are linked together so Google can confirm they describe the same physical business entity.</p>
        <p>A well-built location page functions as five things at once:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>An SEO landing page</strong> — targeting "[service] + [city]" queries for that branch's area</li>
          <li><strong>An entity confirmation signal</strong> — verifying NAP data matches across the web</li>
          <li><strong>A schema carrier</strong> — hosting the LocalBusiness JSON-LD block for that branch</li>
          <li><strong>A conversion page</strong> — giving searchers the specific information they need to visit, call, or book</li>
          <li><strong>A GBP link destination</strong> — the URL each GBP listing's website field should point to</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">BrightLocal research</div>
          <p>Multi-location businesses with individually optimised location pages generate <strong>20-30% more organic traffic per location</strong> than those using a single consolidated locations page. The gap widens in competitive markets where individual branches face separate local competitors.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why location pages matter for local SEO</h2>
        <p>Four mechanisms explain why location pages outperform directory-style location lists:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Individual ranking opportunities.</strong> A single /locations/ page can rank for one location at a time. A dedicated page per branch gives Google a separate URL to rank for each city-specific query — "dental implants Austin" and "dental implants Dallas" can each return their own page.</li>
          <li><strong>GBP connection and map pack eligibility.</strong> Linking each GBP listing to its specific location page creates a confirmed entity match. Google uses this match to boost map pack rankings for location-specific searches.</li>
          <li><strong>LocalBusiness schema hosting.</strong> Each location page carries its own JSON-LD block with that branch's unique address, coordinates, and hours. Copying one schema block across all location pages flags as duplicate structured data.</li>
          <li><strong>Content differentiation.</strong> A branch page that includes that location's staff bios, community involvement, location-specific reviews, and nearby landmarks provides signals no generic template can — these are the differentiators in competitive local markets.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How location pages work — technical setup</h2>
        <p>Building a location page system that Google trusts requires consistent patterns across three areas: URL structure, content, and technical implementation.</p>

        <h3>URL structure</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Recommended subfolder structure</span><br>
          <span class="uf-new">https://example.com/locations/austin/</span> <span class="uf-comment">&#x2713; clean, crawlable, authority-consolidated</span><br>
          <span class="uf-new">https://example.com/locations/dallas/</span><br>
          <span class="uf-new">https://example.com/locations/houston/</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Avoid: subdomains split link equity</span><br>
          <span class="uf-old">https://austin.example.com/</span> <span class="uf-comment">&#x2717; harder to consolidate, weaker SEO by default</span>
        </div>

        <h3>Essential content elements per page</h3>
        <p>Every location page needs all of the following — any missing element weakens its ability to rank and convert:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Branch address (matching GBP exactly)</li>
          <li>Local phone number (not a tracked number that differs from GBP)</li>
          <li>Opening hours</li>
          <li>Embedded Google Map with the specific branch pinned</li>
          <li>Staff names and photos for that branch</li>
          <li>Location-specific services or specialisations</li>
          <li>Customer reviews specific to that location</li>
          <li>LocalBusiness JSON-LD schema with geo-coordinates</li>
          <li>Link to the GBP listing ("View us on Google")</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Content differentiation — the hard part</h3>
        <p>The most common location page failure is template duplication. If your 8 location pages share identical text with only the city name swapped, Google treats them as near-duplicate content and may suppress most of them. Genuine differentiation requires:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Branch manager bio and photo</li>
          <li>Services or specialists unique to that location</li>
          <li>Local community involvement (sponsorships, events)</li>
          <li>Neighbourhood landmarks as directions context</li>
          <li>Reviews pulled from that location's GBP listing specifically</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="types">Location pages vs city pages — key differences</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th></th><th>Location Page</th><th>City Page</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Physical presence</strong></td><td>Required — the business operates here</td><td>Not required — serves the area remotely</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>NAP content</strong></td><td>Branch-specific address and phone</td><td>Service-area business format (no storefront address)</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>GBP link</strong></td><td>Links to that branch's GBP listing</td><td>May link to primary GBP listing</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Schema type</strong></td><td>LocalBusiness with full address + geo</td><td>LocalBusiness with areaServed, no address</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Map pack eligibility</strong></td><td>Yes — can appear in map results for this city</td><td>Limited — depends on proximity and authority</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Content emphasis</strong></td><td>Branch staff, that location's reviews, branch hours</td><td>Area-specific services, local knowledge, community</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real location page examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Dental group with 6 offices</h3>
        <p>A dental group created individual location pages for each of its 6 clinics. Each page featured the clinic's specific dentists, that location's specialty services (e.g., orthodontics available only at 2 of 6), hours, parking instructions, and 15 embedded reviews from that clinic's GBP. Within 4 months, all 6 locations appeared in map pack results for city-specific queries — up from 2 locations before the project.</p>

        <h3>2. Franchise fitness chain</h3>
        <p>A fitness franchise with 22 locations used a template base for efficiency, then added mandatory unique sections: the local manager's fitness background, the nearest public transport stop, that gym's class schedule (which varied by location), and before/after testimonials from members at that specific club. The pages ranked on average 3.2 positions higher than the identical-template pages they replaced, measured over 90 days.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Location pages vs national SEO — when each applies</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Location pages (local SEO)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Multi-branch businesses: dental, legal, retail, services</li>
              <li>Target "[service] near me" and city-specific queries</li>
              <li>Map pack visibility is the primary ranking surface</li>
              <li>NAP, GBP, and schema are the core ranking signals</li>
              <li>Conversion happens via phone calls, directions, walk-ins</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>National SEO pages</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Single-location or online-only businesses</li>
              <li>Target broader, non-location-modified queries</li>
              <li>Organic results (blue links) are the primary surface</li>
              <li>Backlinks, content depth, and authority drive rankings</li>
              <li>Conversion happens via form fills, trials, purchases</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for location pages</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>One page per physical location, no exceptions.</strong> Never share a URL between two branches or use one page for a whole region. Google ranks pages, not categories.</li>
          <li><strong>Use subfolder URLs, not subdomains.</strong> <code>/locations/austin/</code> consolidates link equity under your main domain. Subdomains split authority and require separate SEO effort.</li>
          <li><strong>Link each GBP listing to its exact location page.</strong> Not the homepage, not the /locations/ index — the specific branch page. This is the entity connection Google uses for map pack ranking.</li>
          <li><strong>Match NAP exactly between the page and GBP.</strong> "Suite 4" vs "Ste. 4" creates entity mismatch. Copy-paste from GBP, never retype.</li>
          <li><strong>Embed a Google Map with the branch pinned.</strong> Embedded maps add a geographic signal to the page and improve conversion for visitors checking directions.</li>
          <li><strong>Add location-specific schema with geo-coordinates.</strong> Use the full <code>LocalBusiness</code> JSON-LD with latitude and longitude, not just an address string.</li>
          <li><strong>Refresh the page quarterly.</strong> Update reviews, staff changes, seasonal hours, and new services. Fresh content increases crawl frequency and signals the page is actively maintained.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — identical template pages with only the city name swapped</div>
          <p>Creating 15 location pages from a single template where only the city name changes is the most common multi-location SEO failure. Google identifies near-duplicate content and typically ranks one or two instances while suppressing the rest. The fix is genuine differentiation: different staff, different services, different reviews, different content — not just different place names.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common location page mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Linking GBP to the homepage</strong> — breaks the entity connection between each listing and its specific page.</li>
          <li><strong>Using a shared phone number across all location pages</strong> — NAP must be unique per location; a central call-routing number that differs from GBP creates entity conflict.</li>
          <li><strong>Omitting staff and local content</strong> — pages without unique people and local context look identical to Google and get treated as duplicates.</li>
          <li><strong>Not adding LocalBusiness schema</strong> — the page has no machine-readable confirmation of its geographic entity.</li>
          <li><strong>Blocking location pages in robots.txt</strong> — seen more than you'd expect on franchise sites where head office IT restricts crawling of branch pages.</li>
          <li><strong>Not building internal links to location pages</strong> — location pages buried deep in a site receive minimal crawl budget and build no authority from the main domain.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
